(e') Att. iii. 12, 3, ci donatam M; Sidona tamen A: there is not much to ohoose between obviously corrupt words and an obviously futile attempt at correction, if one is secking only to find out what Cicero wrote; but when one is estimating the comparative value of two mss, the differenoe becomes important. One looks for a clue for the real words not in the mistaken correction, but in the corrupt words. The ms which gives the corrupt words without any attempt at emendation is plainly the more valuable.
